items.title: I personally think it’s a great collaboration
items.content_html:
@lookbackbmx

I personally think it’s a great collaboration. Two American giants. And generally the Supreme stuff (clothing) is of a good quality using American made blanks but also their cut n sew. You can’t knock @moeller_chris for this one. He’s put the work in over the years for sure. Just a shame the fools have to play these ball games on eBay. No denying it looks cool as fuck!

items.content_html:
@lookbackbmx

Come on then. What 80s BMX superstar had input into this. There’s a few E.T esque radical stunts going on and the bike design is something to die for (or of). Check out the trailer on YT, possibly the most underrated BMX movie of all time. Where is this bike now?

items.title: Looks legit
items.content_html:
@lookbackbmx

Looks legit. . (It’s worth noting here, Supreme are not the ones who are charging £10,000 for a bike. It’s the resellers capitalising on highly desirable trending items. There’s no real way around it, but all the bad publicity they get as a result is genius marketing for them - everyone loves a bad guy right?)

items.title: The goose is finally loose
items.content_html:
@northeastbadboys

The goose is finally loose. We present to you the Silly Goose. A made in Maine collaboration with @stovedialer we spent months of intense r&d that included doing wheelies on fairdales up the Maine coast to eat gelato at lighthouses and other non sprocket developing and testing activities. 30, 33, and 36t sizes in black or clear anodize available now in our web store along with our new longsleeve and pocket tees. Oh ya don’t drink warm beer. So pumped to finally release these sick birds into the wild. Shout out @stovedialer, @galster.art @plusjoshsmith and @negativepresspvd for all the help. LINCOLN BYEOHH.

items.title: I've got a BMX theory about how riding without bra…
items.content_html:
@tajlucas

I've got a BMX theory about how riding without brakes has made more things possible (at 2pm on a saturday, during a snowstorm, 10 years after I retired from BMX). Back in my day, riding with brakes was the standard. I'm not sure why we say "brakes" even though it generally means back brake only... people with front brakes were always weird (@mikeescamilla, @daveybaco). With a finger covering the brake lever your wrist ends up kind of locked in place. I used to make fun of riders who had a "mantis" riding style where they rode with their wrists rolled back. Flatlanders used to do it a lot while doing nose wheelies, which should have been a giveaway that it was useful. In my mind, the potential for hard landings meant I should keep my wrist in an about-to-punch-something position at all times. I assumed riding with my wrist loose would mean I'd break it. From my old-washed-up-pro position on the sidelines, I see things differently now. I briefly rode without "brakes"– enough to realize it has a fantastic effect on balance and go-for-it-ness. Somehow just taking my hand off the lever wasn't the same as taking the lever off the bike. You start getting more in tune with your bike because you're going to die if you don't. But it's more than that. Watching today's riding, I 'm no longer bothered by the occasional mantis style since wrist position seems to freely change depending on what balance demands. Freeing the wrist from being locked in position by the brake lever's placement seems to have added a level of dynamism to BMX that didn't used to exist. I think it is probably like riding in ski boots that don't allow you to bend your ankle and then switching to some low top shoes. It might seem subtle but that additional movement in the bike's cockpit adds up to all kinds of new things.

items.content_html:
@tajlucas

items.title: Fundraiser via @homegrownskate-
items.content_html:
@radshare

Fundraiser via @homegrownskate- For the release of the @cncpts x @nikesb Duck High Pro I’ve partnered up with my good friend @crandallfbm and his non-profit @radshare along with @copdate in order to give back one more time in what’s been a difficult year for so many. —— NET PROCEEDS from all of your entries will be donated to Radshare in order to purchase complete Skateboards and BMX bikes for kids in underserved communities, hopefully bringing a little bit of joy to some during a time when everyone needs it. —— For this fundraiser I’m running both LOCAL and NATIONWIDE events giving everyone a chance to participate.  Entry is via LINK ONLY which can be found in my bio or in the story post.  Registration is open from now until 1:30pm ET 11/21.  There will be a separate post with updates for pick up instructions and any follow up information Tuesday 11/24. —— TRIPLE BOOST ENTRIES QUALIFY FOR: - Concepts Dunk and NEXT 10 Homegrown x Copdate drops GUARANTEED.  (1 local, 1 national winner) - Concepts Dunk and Next Drop guaranteed. (2 local, 2 national winners) - Concepts Dunk —— DOUBLE BOOST ENTRIES QUALIFY FOR: - Concepts Dunk and Next Drop guaranteed. (2 local, 2 national winners) - Concepts Dunk (Local and national) —— SINGLE BOOST ENTRIES (no purchase necessary) QUALIFY FOR: - Concepts Dunk (Local and national) —— As always, thank you all for supporting the shop and these efforts to give back.  The first fundraiser I did earlier in the year raised $50k for our local community center thanks to all of your generosity.  I’m hoping this round will be just as successful, and that it will provide something meaningful for many families this holiday season.  Good luck to all! -Andrew

items.title: We are stoked to announce our latest BIKE GIVEAWAY
items.content_html:
@radshare

We are stoked to announce our latest BIKE GIVEAWAY! Through the generosity our amazing partners and donors, RADshare was able to donate more than 100 helmets as well as bikes last year to underserved and underrepresented kids across the country. We are all about getting our local community stoked on BMX and now we want to do that with a little ripper in your area. If you know someone that could use a new Kink Curb and Shadow helmet let us know why in the comments and we’ll choose a worthy recipient February 24th. We’ve got some BIG things happening this year so keep an eye out. We are looking forward to sharing the stoke with you all!

items.title: Part of our goal with RADshare is to work within B…
items.content_html:
@radshare

Part of our goal with RADshare is to work within BMX to help share more opportunities and good times with young riders. Our recent effort with @drop_in_coffee and @rothrockcoffee gave us a chance to purchase some helmets from @theshadowconspiracy. We will be at @richmondbmx this Saturday around noon doing a few giveaways with some special guests and breaking in the track for the season opener, which will be on March 7th. If you are around, come say hi and help us share the stoke with the next generation of BMXers...

items.title: The events surrounding this photo were nothing sho…
items.content_html:
@crandallfbm

The events surrounding this photo were nothing short of outrageous. A quick bike-camping adventure in PR with John Tillman, where we met up with @superbmx and @russbarone who happened to be there as well. The first night there was an earthquake, which was part of a series that sparked tragedy. The following night a meteor visibly crashed into the ocean near our campsite, then a storm came and left us stranded on Culebra for several days, and that’s just part of the story. Life’s a beach...

items.title: When I was 4 my Dad taught me how to ride a bike
items.content_html:
@crandallfbm

When I was 4 my Dad taught me how to ride a bike. Years later getting to see him decked out in FBM gear, riding a couple red bikes made in our factory in upstate Ny, was a pretty big deal to me. I don’t think he’d ridden a bicycle in ages, but man, that smile gets me so stoked. Happy Birthday to the OG Steve Crandall, miss you everyday...
